messages.content: Why are so many reporters dead set on making totalitarian regimes look better than the US
I've had family members disappear in Syria because of mere suspicion by the gov
@Syrian Barbarian It's a lack of reference frame

> I've had family members disappear in Syria because of mere suspicion by the gov
@Syrian Barbarian welcome to modern day india
when you have a shit economy, the only way to control people is by controlling the media and enforcing forceful policing
Yup people have no perspective of what goes on outside their bubble
But you expect better from reporters

Reporters in the normal world (outside of North-America/EU) can't really have families and do great reporting at the same time. Its a great sacrifice on the reporters end where they live in fear of their own life/job let alone their family's life as well. In India were family formation is more of a 'forced social construct' reporters can only do so much as reporter threats can extend into extended family or where ever the weak points are. This is why they may not break stories that may break their family. India's gov't, although a parliamentary democracy, is only a democracy if the ruling party chooses it to be one. Thats the issue with parliamentary top-down gov't, which we don't have here in the US as you have counties, state gov, state legislature, federal legislature, circuit courts, district courts, the executive branch, and the supreme court in friction with each other. Hence in 1 way or another, the culture or reporters reporting on things is intact with a US passport. So I don't fault the reporters. 

Recently, a leading indian news tv executive editor started a new job as Associate Professor at Harvard's School of Journalism and their Twitter flipped from being very pro gov't for the sake of their safety to a more balanced pro/anti current gov't. Being in US allows them that advantage, something which reporters born here do take very much for granted.
